{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01ADiVG1wwYp2MZndLWSZWef","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\nThe core problem in this experiment is a **feature formulation** issue, not a feature selection issue. Round 2 showed that KV features have signal (kv_sum correlates with step time) but Ridge regression with raw features spanning 5 orders of magnitude (tokens 0–2K vs kv_sum 0–64K) causes coefficient instability. FairBatching's insight is using a minimal 3-coefficient OLS model where each feature has its own well-conditioned coefficient. This is a classic bias-variance tradeoff: fewer parameters = more stable coefficients, even if each feature individually explains less variance.\n`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`\n\nNow let me create the sub-hypothesis directories and write the experiment code. I'll create a combined Python script that handles H1 and H2 (both are per-step ML experiments), and then H3 (BLIS E2E validation) separately."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"27497e41-6ff8-42ab-aee1-66206c73fdbf","uuid":"477bf27a-619f-475f-809a-2a80a0ac8866"}
